english:
  title: A Letter Dispatching Sari-ta, an Official
  author: Lee Kyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I respectfully submit this letter. As early summer arrives, I humbly trust that you remain in good health and blessed with ten thousand fortunes.

    Regarding the matter you previously mentioned—to bring one thousand fine otter pelts as tribute to the Emperor—in our country, we have never before hunted such creatures. Only after your esteemed nation requested them did we begin to pursue them with every method, yet we cannot capture them in great abundance. Thus each time we prepare our tribute, it becomes a hardship. Now the quantity you seek is excessive, and though we search, such pelts remain difficult to obtain. We cannot meet your expectations fully. Yet we have scoured the distant corners of our realm, gathering and storing month after month. Still we cannot reach the full number. We humbly send nine hundred seventy-seven pelts, trusting you will understand the circumstance.

    Concerning your requirement that we send five hundred young men and five hundred young women from the royal family, princes, and officials—as I have written before, our nation's law permits even the king himself but one legitimate consort; we have no concubines. Therefore the branches of our royal line do not flourish abundantly. Moreover, our country is small, and the officials in our court number barely two thousand five hundred. Each takes but one wife, and their offspring are few or none at all. If we were to send all such people to your great nation, who would inherit the throne and fill the offices of state to serve you? I earnestly beseech your mighty nation to show mercy upon our small and weak land, to preserve our good relations for ten thousand generations, and to remit such demands that our humble territory cannot bear—thus demonstrating the virtue of cherishing the small and supporting the weak.

    As for the matter of sending various craftsmen: our country has always lacked such artisans. Moreover, famine and pestilence have claimed many lives. Added to this, your noble nation's armies have passed through our great and small fortresses, leaving many harmed and displaced. Since then our craftsmen have scattered, with none remaining to establish themselves in their trades. Therefore we cannot fulfill this requirement according to your command. All this I report truthfully, and I humbly beseech your compassionate understanding of our distress.

    Regarding the matter of investigating the households of Uiju that belong to Zhao's military administration: I have already issued orders to the military authorities of that region to inquire thoroughly into this matter. They report that the fortress commander and the people attempted to escape by raft but were capsized and drowned by the wind. Thus we cannot provide clear verification. I trust you will understand this circumstance.

    As for all other matters mentioned in your letter, we shall attend to them one by one according to your wishes.

    Concerning the lean horses left behind when your forces withdrew: we have gathered them from all places—fifteen in total—and have arranged for their care and feeding. We shall send them along with this embassy.
  footnotes:
    - Sari-ta (撒里打) was likely a Mongol official, given the context of this letter being addressed to a superior power making tributary demands.
    - The otter pelts (水獺皮) were prized tribute items in the Yuan court, reflecting the Mongol appreciation for luxurious furs.
    - Lee Kyu-bo addresses the impossible demands with diplomatic restraint, emphasizing both his nation's constraints and its desire to maintain peaceful relations with its powerful neighbor.
